In article <2khc5b$7nv@rand.org> jim@rand.org (Jim Gillogly) writes:
>In article <9402142102.AA00787@mhiba3.rvax4>,
>Hibbard M. Engler <rhib@rvax4.syntex.com> wrote:
>>If the encryption function is truely one way (not one to one), then 
>>many passowrds could in rare cases map to the same encryption string, 
>>and I think that is less secure than a one-to-one system.
>
>It's probably not one-to-one, and it's quite likely that many passwords map
>to the same encryption string.  I've never seen it happen, though, and it's
>low enough probability that it wont give you any mileage.
>
>[outlines expression of the modified DES as boolean functions]
[more deletia]
>
>Yes (assuming the final munging into 2+11 printable characters is
>reversible), but totally impractical because of the intermediate expressions.

It should be noted that, in general, solving a system of boolean equations
is NP-hard, so this approach doesn't seem promising.  The total number of
terms, even with a dramatic amount of simplification, would probably be
too large for current SAT heuristics to handle.
